---
import Layout from '../../components/Layout.astro';
import hostCities from '../../data/world-cup-aviation/host-cities.json';
import airportCsv from '../../data/world-cup-aviation/faa-2024-enplanements.csv?raw';
import pressureCsv from '../../data/world-cup-aviation/pressure-index.csv?raw';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const tags = ['Aviation Networks', 'Transportation Geography', 'World Cup 2026', 'Airline Operations', 'Aviation Resilience'];
const parseCsv = (raw: string) => {
  const [header, ...rows] = raw.trim().split('\n').map((row) => row.split(','));
  return rows.map((row) => Object.fromEntries(header.map((key, index) => [key, row[index]])));
};
const airports = parseCsv(airportCsv);
const pressure = parseCsv(pressureCsv);
const comparisonCodes = ['ATL', 'DFW', 'LAX', 'JFK', 'MIA', 'SEA', 'SFO', 'EWR', 'IAH', 'MCI'];
const comparisonAirports = comparisonCodes.map((code) => airports.find((airport) => airport.airport === code)!);
const maxAirportVolume = Math.max(...comparisonAirports.map((airport) => Number(airport.cy2024_enplanements)));
const mapX = (lon: number) => ((lon + 125) / 60) * 900;
const mapY = (lat: number) => ((55 - lat) / 36) * 480;
const points = Object.fromEntries(hostCities.map((city) => [city.city, { x: mapX(city.lon), y: mapY(city.lat) }]));
const links = [
  ['Seattle', 'Los Angeles'], ['Los Angeles', 'Dallas'], ['Dallas', 'Houston'], ['Houston', 'Atlanta'],
  ['Atlanta', 'New York/New Jersey'], ['New York/New Jersey', 'Boston'], ['Dallas', 'Kansas City'],
  ['San Francisco Bay Area', 'Seattle'], ['Miami', 'Atlanta'], ['Toronto', 'New York/New Jersey'],
];
const cityLabel = (city: string) => ({'New York/New Jersey':'NY/NJ','San Francisco Bay Area':'Bay Area','Mexico City':'Mexico City','Kansas City':'Kansas City'}[city] || city);
const formatMillions = (value: string | number) => `${(Number(value) / 1_000_000).toFixed(1)}M`;
---

<Layout
  title="How the 2026 FIFA World Cup Is Stress-Testing America's Air Travel Network"
  description="A data-supported analysis of World Cup travel demand, hub congestion, and aviation resilience."
  image={`${base}research/world-cup-network-hero.png`}
  type="article"
>
  <article>
    <header class="article-hero">
      <img src={`${base}research/world-cup-network-hero.png`} alt="Flight paths connecting airport hubs across North America" />
      <div class="hero-shade"></div>
      <div class="container hero-content">
        <a class="back-link" href={`${base}research`}>&lt;- Research</a>
        <p class="page-kicker">Data-supported research commentary</p>
        <h1>How the 2026 FIFA World Cup Is Stress-Testing America's Air Travel Network</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Aviation demand, hub congestion, and transportation resilience during the largest World Cup in history.</p>
        <div class="byline"><span>Hexin Yu</span><span>Updated June 19, 2026</span><span>12 min read</span></div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="container article-grid">
      <aside class="article-aside"><p>Filed under</p><div class="tags">{tags.map((tag) => <span>{tag}</span>)}</div></aside>
      <div class="prose">
        <section>
          <h2>Introduction</h2>
          <p class="standfirst">A World Cup match begins at kickoff, but its transportation footprint begins days earlier and hundreds or thousands of miles away.</p>
          <p>The 2026 tournament temporarily reorganizes passenger movement across North America. Supporters arrive through international gateways, connect at airline hubs, and move between host cities on schedules determined partly by match results. The aviation question is therefore not simply whether airports become busy. It is where event traffic overlaps with large baseline passenger flows, tightly connected airline networks, and constrained match-day operating windows.</p>
          <p>The data does not support a claim that demand will surge everywhere. Instead, it identifies an uneven geography of exposure: New York/New Jersey has the final and a three-airport gateway; Dallas has nine matches and a major connecting hub; Houston combines seven matches with two commercial airports and special FAA traffic procedures. Other cities have fewer matches, smaller airport baselines, or weaker booking growth.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Why World Cup 2026 Matters for Aviation</h2>
          <p>FIFA's official schedule contains <strong>104 matches across 16 host cities in three countries</strong>. The United States hosts 78 matches, Canada 13, and Mexico 13. Dallas has nine matches; Atlanta, Los Angeles, and New York/New Jersey have eight each. That distribution matters because knockout-stage trips cannot be fully planned until teams advance.</p>
          <p>FIFA designed regional groupings to reduce travel, but the host footprint still stretches from Vancouver to Miami and from Los Angeles to Boston. Unlike ordinary leisure demand, match travel is fixed to a destination and time. Passengers can change flights or hotels, but they cannot move the match. This makes short demand peaks more operationally important than tournament-wide totals alone.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="method-box">
          <p class="eyebrow">Data and methodology</p>
          <h2>What is measured - and what is not</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Official schedule:</strong> FIFA host-city allocations provide total, group-stage, and knockout match counts.</li>
            <li><strong>Pre-event baseline:</strong> FAA CY2024 ACAIS enplanements measure departing revenue passengers. They indicate airport scale, not 2026 demand or aircraft operations.</li>
            <li><strong>Exploratory index:</strong> Equal weights combine normalized match count, metro-airport enplanements, and FAA hub class. The index is descriptive, not a delay forecast.</li>
            <li><strong>Interpretation:</strong> Sojern booking signals, FAA event procedures, industry guidance, and my Houston observations help explain mechanisms. They do not prove that the World Cup caused a specific delay.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="source-note">Processed files: <code>src/data/world-cup-aviation/</code>. The methodology and source notes are documented in the accompanying README.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="dark-figure map-figure">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 900 500" role="img" aria-labelledby="fig1-title fig1-desc">
            <title id="fig1-title">World Cup host city aviation map</title>
            <desc id="fig1-desc">All sixteen host cities, with circles sized by official FIFA match count and selected inter-city links.</desc>
            <path class="land" d="M18 55 L145 22 305 43 410 75 520 72 665 108 841 151 884 255 828 347 720 382 630 450 486 460 352 416 247 433 160 340 70 287Z" />
            <g class="routes">{links.map(([from, to]) => <line x1={points[from].x} y1={points[from].y} x2={points[to].x} y2={points[to].y} />)}</g>
            <g class="nodes">{hostCities.map((city) => <g><circle class:list={{focus: city.city === 'Houston'}} cx={mapX(city.lon)} cy={mapY(city.lat)} r={5 + city.matches * 1.25}/><text x={mapX(city.lon) + 12} y={mapY(city.lat) - 11}>{cityLabel(city.city)}</text><text class="airport-label" x={mapX(city.lon) + 12} y={mapY(city.lat) + 5}>{city.airportCodes.join('/')} · {city.matches}</text></g>)}</g>
          </svg>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 1.</strong> All 16 FIFA host cities. Marker area reflects official match count; labels show nearby gateway code(s) and matches. Lines are selected analytical links, not scheduled routes. <span>Source: FIFA official 2026 match schedule; airport assignment by author.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Host city schedule table" tabindex="0">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Host city</th><th>Country</th><th>Airport(s)</th><th>Group</th><th>Knockout</th><th>Total</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>{hostCities.map((city) => <tr><td>{city.city}</td><td>{city.country}</td><td>{city.airportCodes.join(', ')}</td><td>{city.groupMatches}</td><td>{city.knockoutMatches}</td><td><strong>{city.matches}</strong></td></tr>)}</tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="table-caption"><strong>Table 1.</strong> Host-city match allocations and associated major commercial gateways. Source: FIFA official schedule.</p>

        <section>
          <h2>Host Cities and Airport Baselines</h2>
          <p>Baseline airport scale shows why an identical match-day pulse would not have an identical operational meaning everywhere. ATL recorded 52.5 million enplanements in 2024, compared with 5.9 million at MCI. DFW handled 42.4 million; IAH handled 23.3 million before adding Hobby's 7.1 million. Large volume can provide more routes and recovery options, but it also means event traffic enters an already dense schedule.</p>
          <p>This baseline does not measure spare capacity. A large airport may absorb additional passengers efficiently, while a smaller airport may have more available gates at a particular hour. It does, however, identify where World Cup flows intersect with the largest existing passenger systems.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="chart-figure">
          <div class="chart-title"><span>CY2024 revenue passenger enplanements</span><strong>FAA pre-event baseline</strong></div>
          <div class="bar-chart">{comparisonAirports.map((airport) => <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">{airport.airport}</span><div class="bar-track"><span style={`width:${Number(airport.cy2024_enplanements) / maxAirportVolume * 100}%`}></span></div><strong>{formatMillions(airport.cy2024_enplanements)}</strong></div>)}</div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 2.</strong> Departing revenue passengers at selected host-city airports. This is an annual 2024 baseline, not World Cup traffic and not aircraft operations. <span>Source: FAA CY2024 ACAIS commercial-service enplanements.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Hub Airports and Network Pressure</h2>
          <p>Hub-and-spoke airlines redistribute passengers from many origins through connecting airports. ATL, DFW, and IAH are both host-city gateways and transfer hubs. ORD, DEN, and CLT are not host cities, but their schedules can feed passengers toward several tournament markets. This creates reach and flexibility while coupling operations across cities.</p>
          <p><strong>The World Cup turns the airline network into a live stress test: when one hub slows down, delays can quickly spread across the system.</strong> A late inbound aircraft can create missed connections, delay its next departure, and displace passengers onto later flights. This mechanism is well established, but the charts below show exposure rather than causation.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="chart-figure index-figure">
          <div class="chart-title"><span>Exploratory pressure index</span><strong>0-100 screening score</strong></div>
          <div class="bar-chart">{pressure.map((row) => <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label city">{row.rank}. {row.host_city}</span><div class="bar-track"><span style={`width:${row.pressure_index}%`}></span></div><strong>{row.pressure_index}</strong></div>)}</div>
          <div class="formula">100 × (normalized matches + normalized metro enplanements + FAA hub score) / 3</div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 3.</strong> A transparent, equal-weight exploratory index. It suggests where tournament load and baseline network scale overlap; it does not predict delay or capacity failure. <span>Sources: FIFA schedule; FAA CY2024 ACAIS; calculations by author.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="dark-figure flow-figure">
          <div class="flow-head"><span>Network disruption</span><span>Connecting hubs</span><span>Downstream hosts</span></div>
          <svg viewBox="0 0 900 380" role="img" aria-labelledby="fig4-title fig4-desc">
            <title id="fig4-title">Delay propagation concept diagram</title><desc id="fig4-desc">Weather or capacity constraints move through major connecting hubs to downstream host cities.</desc>
            <g class="flow-lines"><path d="M110 85 C260 85 290 80 430 80 S630 70 790 70"/><path d="M110 190 C270 190 280 145 430 145 S630 150 790 150"/><path d="M110 295 C270 295 280 210 430 210 S630 220 790 230"/><path d="M110 85 C270 85 280 275 430 275 S630 285 790 310"/></g>
            <g class="origin"><circle cx="110" cy="85" r="12"/><text x="25" y="90">Thunderstorms</text><circle cx="110" cy="190" r="12"/><text x="23" y="195">Gate limits</text><circle cx="110" cy="295" r="12"/><text x="24" y="300">ATC flow</text></g>
            <g class="hubs"><circle cx="430" cy="80" r="18"/><text x="462" y="85">ATL / DFW</text><circle class="delayed" cx="430" cy="145" r="22"/><text x="470" y="150">IAH</text><circle cx="430" cy="210" r="18"/><text x="462" y="215">ORD</text><circle cx="430" cy="275" r="18"/><text x="462" y="280">DEN / CLT</text></g>
            <g class="dest"><circle cx="790" cy="70" r="12"/><text x="815" y="75">Missed connections</text><circle cx="790" cy="150" r="12"/><text x="815" y="155">Late aircraft</text><circle cx="790" cy="230" r="12"/><text x="815" y="235">Crew displacement</text><circle cx="790" cy="310" r="12"/><text x="815" y="315">Host-city delays</text></g>
          </svg>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 4.</strong> Conceptual delay propagation through major hubs. The diagram describes a mechanism; it does not report observed World Cup delay. <span>Author's diagram informed by hub-and-spoke operations.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Houston Case Study</h2>
          <p>I attended Germany versus Curaçao at Houston Stadium on June 14. The match turned Houston from an abstract map node into a practical example of layered transportation demand: international and domestic arrivals entered through IAH and Hobby, visitors accumulated downtown, and a large crowd converged on one stadium district at a fixed time.</p>
          <p>Official baseline data puts the airport system in context. IAH and HOU recorded 30.5 million combined enplanements in 2024, while Houston's seven matches include two knockout fixtures. FAA event guidance also imposed Prior Permission Required procedures for area airports and warned pilots to expect traffic-management initiatives. Those facts indicate potential concentration; they do not prove that the match caused a particular commercial delay.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="houston-panel">
          <div class="houston-stats"><p class="eyebrow">Houston / field note</p><h3>Two airports, seven matches, one timed convergence</h3><dl><div><dt>30.5M</dt><dd>IAH + HOU CY2024 enplanements</dd></div><div><dt>7</dt><dd>Houston matches</dd></div><div><dt>68,021</dt><dd>Germany-Curaçao attendance observed on the stadium display</dd></div><div><dt>73 min</dt><dd>Average delay shown in my June 15 airport-app screenshot; observational, not FAA-validated</dd></div></dl></div>
          <div class="photo-placeholder"><span>PERSONAL FIELD EVIDENCE</span><strong>Houston match-day photograph</strong><p>Reserved for the original stadium image and airport screenshot.</p></div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 5.</strong> Houston combines official airport scale and match allocation with first-hand observations. The app screenshot is contextual evidence only and cannot establish World Cup causality. <span>Sources: FAA CY2024 ACAIS; FIFA schedule; personal observations.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Uneven Impact Across Cities</h2>
          <p>The pressure index ranks New York/New Jersey, Dallas, and Atlanta highest because each combines many matches with a large airport system and hub status. Kansas City ranks lower because MCI's passenger baseline is smaller, but that should not be read as “no pressure.” A smaller system can still face sharp peaks, limited nonstop options, or business-aviation parking constraints.</p>
          <p>Demand evidence is also uneven. Sojern reported April booking growth of 42% for Dallas and 38% for Houston, but a 16% decline for Seattle. Reuters later reported that high ticket prices and complex international travel weakened the expected benefit for some U.S. airlines and hotels. The data suggests concentration and mismatch, not a uniform continental surge.</p>
          <p>Business aviation adds another layer. NBAA advises operators to secure required reservations and expect holding or surface delays; Universal Weather identifies slot, parking, permit, and security pressure. FAA procedures coordinate scarce airspace and ramp access through flight-plan windows, ground-delay programs, TFRs, and airport-specific permissions.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>What This Means for Aviation Research</h2>
          <p>The World Cup creates a useful natural experiment. The match schedule supplies known demand events; FAA OPSNET and BTS TranStats can supply subsequent operations, delay, and passenger outcomes. After the tournament, daily data can test whether host airports experienced statistically unusual volumes or delays relative to comparable summer days.</p>
          <p>Useful next steps include matching flight-level on-time records to match windows, measuring recovery time after each peak, and comparing hubs with regional gateways. This does not prove causality by itself, but it can show where operational pressure concentrated, how disruption propagated, and whether secondary airports increased resilience.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="references">
          <h2>References</h2>
          <ol>
            <li><a href="https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/match-schedule-fixtures-results-teams-stadiums" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FIFA. “FIFA World Cup 2026 Match Schedule.”</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/arp-cy2024-commercial-service-enplanements.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FAA. “CY2024 Enplanements at All Commercial Service Airports.” September 15, 2025.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.aspm.faa.gov/opsnet/sys/main.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FAA. Operations Network (OPSNET), official air traffic operations and delay data.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.transtats.bts.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bureau of Transportation Statistics. TranStats aviation databases, including T-100 and On-Time Performance.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.faa.gov/fifaworldcup2026" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FAA. “FAA's Safety Plan for FIFA World Cup 2026.” Updated June 1, 2026.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://nbaa.org/aircraft-operations/airspace/regional/fifa-world-cup-2026/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NBAA. “FIFA World Cup 2026.” Updated June 11, 2026.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.universalweather.com/blog/2026-world-cup-business-aviation-planning-guide-2/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Universal Weather and Aviation. “2026 World Cup: Business Aviation Planning Guide.” January 21, 2026.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.sojern.com/press-release/sojern-data-majority-of-fifa-world-cup-2026-host-cities-see-double-digit-increases-in-flight-bookings-two-months-ahead-of-tournament" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Sojern. “Majority of FIFA World Cup 2026 Host Cities See Double-Digit Increases in Flight Bookings.” April 16, 2026.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://m.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/analysispricey-world-cup-keeps-fans-away-hits-us-hotels-airlines-4736887" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Reuters. “Pricey World Cup Keeps Fans Away, Hits U.S. Hotels, Airlines.” June 11, 2026.</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.bilibili.com/video/BV17EJG67EFa/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Airfun007. “The 2026 World Cup Is Having a Huge Impact on the U.S. Aviation Industry.” Bilibili, June 15, 2026.</a></li>
          </ol>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

